>The point is not that one compiler is any better than another.
>The point is that all tools have their tradeoffs--overcoming
>a tool's limitations or flaws should be considered a standard
>part of building a product. If someone discovers a new flaw or
>has a story to tell about how a set of tradeoffs didn't match
>their project, then fine: this is valuable information. But,
>when *blame* enters the picture, then value erodes: where
>people expend effort acomplishing nothing.

